---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { FAQ } from "../data/faq.ts";

const description =
  "How generative weather art is made - real atmospheric data, 54 global scan points, AI interpretation through 16 artist lenses (7 with custom FLUX.1-dev LoRA fine-tunes), natural scarcity from unrepeatable weather events. By James Tannahill.";

// Strip HTML for FAQ schema text — search engines accept inline HTML in
// answers but stripping keeps the structured data tidy and the visible
// accordion is the source of truth for the rich version.
function stripHtml(s: string) {
  return s
    .replace(/<[^>]+>/g, "")
    .replace(/&mdash;/g, "—")
    .replace(/&amp;/g, "&")
    .replace(/&deg;/g, "°")
    .replace(/&times;/g, "×")
    .replace(/&eacute;/g, "é")
    .replace(/&uuml;/g, "ü");
}

const aboutSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  name: "About art.jt",
  url: "https://art.jamestannahill.com/about/",
  mainEntity: {
    "@type": "Person",
    name: "James Tannahill",
    url: "https://jamestannahill.com",
    email: "art@jamestannahill.com",
    jobTitle: "Generative Artist & Technologist",
    knowsAbout: [
      "Generative Art",
      "Weather Data Visualization",
      "Abstract Expressionism",
      "AWS",
      "AI/ML",
    ],
    sameAs: ["https://jamestannahill.com", "https://github.com/jtannahill"],
  },
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: FAQ.map(({ q, a }) => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    name: q,
    acceptedAnswer: { "@type": "Answer", text: stripHtml(a) },
  })),
};
---

<Base title="About - art.jt" description={description} canonicalPath="/about/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(aboutSchema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <h1>About</h1>

  <nav class="about-nav">
    <a href="#work">The Work</a>
    <a href="#system">The System</a>
    <a href="#method">How It's Made</a>
    <a href="#artist">The Artist</a>
    <a href="#faq">FAQ</a>
  </nav>

  <p class="lede">
    The atmosphere is the oldest artist on Earth. It has been painting since
    before there were eyes to see it &mdash; sculpting light through ice
    crystals, dragging color across horizons, compressing entire landscapes
    into a single hour of sky. This project is an attempt to listen to what
    it's making.
  </p>

  <h2 id="work">The Work</h2>

  <p>
    Every day, fifty-four points across the planet are sampled for what the
    atmosphere is actually doing &mdash; not what it looks like on a forecast,
    but its raw physical state. Pressure gradients steep enough to bend trees.
    Winds crossing open water with nothing to slow them down. Temperature
    anomalies where the air is ten degrees warmer or colder than it should
    be. The ten most extreme conditions become source material for original
    artwork.
  </p>

  <p>
    The data passes through the aesthetic lens of sixteen artists who
    understood that abstraction is not the absence of meaning but its
    distillation. Sam Francis knew that empty space is as charged as color.
    Rothko proved that two rectangles can hold grief. Frankenthaler showed
    that letting paint find its own path is an act of trust. Hilma af Klint
    painted what she believed was invisible.
    <a href="https://lesleytannahill.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
      Lesley Tannahill
    </a>
    builds palimpsests where every mark remembers the marks beneath it.
    These sensibilities are not styles to imitate &mdash; they are ways of
    seeing that transform the same pressure reading into radically different
    compositions.
  </p>

  <p>
    The result is a growing archive of the planet's most volatile moments,
    translated into color and form. No two pieces share the same atmospheric
    conditions. None can be repeated. Each one is a fossil of weather that
    no longer exists.
  </p>

  <h2 id="system">The System</h2>

  <p>
    The pipeline runs at dawn UTC. Weather flows in from the
    <a href="https://open-meteo.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open-Meteo API</a>
    (NOAA's GFS model) and is scored on a composite index &mdash; pressure
    anomaly weighted heaviest, then wind, temperature deviation, precipitation,
    humidity. The highest-scoring conditions are sent to a generative model
    that interprets the atmospheric data as original digital artwork. There
    are three rendering paths: most artists go through Flux 1.1 Pro from a
    descriptive text prompt; seven artists (Lesley Tannahill, Sam Francis,
    Hilma af Klint, Joan Mitchell, Willem de Kooning, Helen Frankenthaler,
    Gerhard Richter) route through custom FLUX.1-dev LoRA fine-tunes trained
    on their own canvas reproductions; and a parallel Claude SVG renderer
    produces a vector version of every piece. Every piece is rendered in
    seven possible canvas formats, from square to panoramic, chosen by the
    conditions themselves. Everything is archived permanently.
  </p>

  <p>
    A parallel system extracts color palettes from Copernicus Sentinel-2
    satellite imagery &mdash; the actual colors of Earth as seen from orbit.
    Deserts, glaciers, river deltas, volcanic islands. A seasonal record of
    what the planet looks like from 786 kilometers up.
  </p>

  <h2 id="method">How the Art Is Made</h2>

  <h3>Artistic Interpretation, Not Imitation</h3>

  <p>
    For most of the artists in the system, no canvas was ever fed to the
    model. Their understanding comes from art criticism, exhibition catalogs,
    and the public discourse around their practices &mdash; the same way a
    human art student learns by reading about artists before they ever pick
    up a brush. Each artist is described to the model in a few sentences
    that capture their visual philosophy: Rothko's luminous floating
    rectangles, Kusama's obsessive dot fields, Mondrian's primary-color
    grid logic. The model doesn't see their paintings. It reads their ideas,
    then writes SVG code or composes a Flux 1.1 Pro prompt from scratch.
    The atmospheric data is the only input. The artist's sensibility is
    the lens.
  </p>

  <p>
    A small number of artists &mdash; currently
    <a href="/artist/lesley_tannahill/">Lesley Tannahill</a>,
    <a href="/artist/sam_francis/">Sam Francis</a>,
    <a href="/artist/hilma_af_klint/">Hilma af Klint</a>,
    <a href="/artist/joan_mitchell/">Joan Mitchell</a>,
    <a href="/artist/willem_de_kooning/">Willem de Kooning</a>,
    <a href="/artist/helen_frankenthaler/">Helen Frankenthaler</a>, and
    <a href="/artist/gerhard_richter/">Gerhard Richter</a> &mdash; take a
    different path. For these, custom <strong>FLUX.1-dev LoRA</strong>
    fine-tunes were trained on small sets of hand-curated canvas
    reproductions, each captioned with title, medium, dimensions, and year.
    The LoRA is a compact set of trainable weights that overlays the much
    larger frozen FLUX.1-dev base, teaching it that artist's specific visual
    language without retraining the whole model. Each of those artists' pages
    carries a "Model &amp; Methodology" block documenting the training set,
    hyperparameters, and provenance.
  </p>

  <h3>Weather Data: 54 Points, 6 Variables</h3>

  <p>
    Every run samples 54 points across 10 latitude bands, from 70&deg;N
    (Arctic) to 60&deg;S (Subantarctic). At each point, six atmospheric
    variables are measured at the current hour:
  </p>

  <div class="vars-grid">
    <span>Sea-level pressure (Pa)</span>
    <span>&rarr; Density, weight, visual mass</span>
    <span>Wind speed &amp; direction</span>
    <span>&rarr; Dynamic energy, directional flow</span>
    <span>Temperature (K)</span>
    <span>&rarr; Color temperature, saturation</span>
    <span>Temperature anomaly</span>
    <span>&rarr; How far from the expected &mdash; the drama</span>
    <span>Relative humidity (%)</span>
    <span>&rarr; Atmospheric moisture, softness</span>
    <span>Precipitation (kg/m&sup2;)</span>
    <span>&rarr; Intensity, texture</span>
  </div>

  <p>
    The composite visual interest score weights these: pressure anomaly
    (30%), wind (25%), temperature deviation (20%), precipitation (15%),
    humidity (10%). The top 10 scorers &mdash; with at least 15&deg; of
    geographic separation to ensure diversity &mdash; become the day's
    artwork subjects.
  </p>

  <h3>Why GFS?</h3>

  <p>
    The weather data comes from NOAA's
    <a
      href="https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/products/weather-climate-models/global-forecast"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener"
    >
      Global Forecast System (GFS)
    </a>, a 0.25&deg; resolution atmospheric model updated every six hours.
    GFS was chosen over alternatives like ECMWF IFS (higher accuracy but
    rate-limited), ICON (better European resolution), or HRRR (3km US-only)
    because it offers the best tradeoff for this project: free global
    coverage at resolution sufficient for macro-scale weather drama, with
    reliable hourly data across all 54 scan points simultaneously. The art
    interprets continental-scale atmospheric patterns &mdash; pressure
    systems spanning oceans, temperature fronts crossing mountain ranges
    &mdash; where GFS excels. The <code>gfs_seamless</code> variant blends
    forecast and analysis data for best-available current conditions.
  </p>

  <h3>Quality Scoring</h3>

  <p>
    After each artwork is generated and rendered to PNG, an AI art critic
    evaluates it on four dimensions: composition, color harmony, complexity,
    and emotional impact. Each piece receives a quality score from 1 to 10.
    This score feeds into the archive, influences print pricing, and helps
    surface the strongest work. The critic sees only the final image &mdash;
    it has no access to the weather data or artist prompt that produced it.
  </p>

  <h3>Weather Forecasting</h3>

  <p>
    Every evening at 20:00 UTC, a separate system scans the 24-hour GFS
    forecast for all 54 scan points, scoring each for predicted visual
    drama using the same composite formula. This produces a ranked list of
    tomorrow's most promising atmospheric conditions &mdash; a weather drama
    forecast that anticipates where the most striking art will come from
    before the pipeline runs.
  </p>

  <h3>Dynamic Pricing</h3>

  <p>
    Print prices are not static. Each artwork's price reflects three
    signals: the quality score from the AI critic (higher-rated work
    commands a premium), the rarity of the weather conditions that produced
    it (extreme atmospheric events are scarcer), and scarcity (as editions
    sell, remaining prints increase in value). The base price can increase
    up to 2&times; for exceptional pieces born from rare weather.
  </p>

  <h3>Natural Scarcity</h3>

  <p>
    Every artwork is generated from a one-time atmospheric event &mdash; a
    specific combination of pressure, wind, temperature, and precipitation
    at a specific location and moment. That weather will never occur again.
    Unlike digital assets where scarcity is manufactured by capping supply,
    the scarcity here is physical: the atmosphere produced it once, and it's
    gone. The artwork is a fossil of a moment that no longer exists.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is closer to photography than to minting &mdash; capturing
    something real, unrepeatable, and time-bound. The atmospheric data is
    archived alongside every piece, timestamped and verifiable against
    NOAA's public records. The weather happened. The art it produced is the
    only one of its kind. Limited edition prints (5 per size) add a physical
    layer of scarcity on top of a natural one. When the last print of a
    piece sells, that's it &mdash; the weather is gone, the edition is
    closed, and the work exists only in the hands of its collectors.
  </p>

  <h2 id="artist">The Artist</h2>

  <p>
    I'm
    <a href="https://jamestannahill.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
      James Tannahill
    </a>. I grew up staring at maps the way other people stared at posters
    &mdash; tracing coastlines, memorizing the shapes of countries I'd never
    visit, trying to understand how a flat sheet of paper could contain an
    ocean. That impulse never went away. It just found new material.
  </p>

  <p>
    Weather is the map I can't finish reading. It is planetary-scale,
    constantly rewriting itself, and fundamentally invisible at any useful
    resolution. You can stand in a storm and still only experience a pinhole
    of what the system is doing. This project is my way of seeing more of
    it &mdash; using the language of the painters who taught me that seeing
    is not passive, that abstraction is a form of attention, and that the
    most honest response to something overwhelming is to let it move through
    you and onto the canvas.
  </p>

  <p>
    The data is real. The locations are real. The weather happened. What
    the machine makes of it &mdash; and what you make of that &mdash; is
    where the art lives.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>

  <div class="faq">
    {
      FAQ.map(({ q, a }) => (
        <details>
          <summary>{q}</summary>
          <p set:html={a} />
        </details>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <div class="cta">
    <p>
      Limited edition prints on Hahnem&uuml;hle German Etching available on
      every artwork page. For commercial licensing, commissions, or
      collaboration: <a href="mailto:art@jamestannahill.com">art@jamestannahill.com</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; margin: 0 0 1rem; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 2.5rem 0 1rem; letter-spacing: -0.01em; }
  h3 {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  p { color: #bbb; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 1.5rem; }
  p.lede {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: #ddd;
    line-height: 1.9;
    font-style: italic;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  code {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    background: #1a1a2e;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: 3px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
  }

  .about-nav {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    padding: 1rem 0;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #222;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .about-nav a {
    color: var(--color-muted);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color 0.2s;
  }
  .about-nav a:hover { color: var(--color-accent); }
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .about-nav { gap: 1rem; }
    .about-nav a { font-size: 0.8rem; }
  }

  .vars-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 0.5rem 2rem;
    color: #999;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    padding: 0 0.5rem;
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .vars-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.25rem; }
  }

  .faq details {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    border: 1px solid #2a2a2a;
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: #111;
  }
  .faq summary {
    padding: 1rem;
    cursor: pointer;
    color: #fff;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    list-style: none;
  }
  .faq summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  .faq summary::after {
    content: "+";
    float: right;
    color: var(--color-muted);
    font-weight: 400;
    transition: transform 0.2s;
  }
  .faq details[open] summary::after { content: "−"; }
  .faq p {
    padding: 0 1rem 1rem;
    color: #bbb;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .cta {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding: 1.2rem;
    background: #111;
    border: 1px solid #2a2a2a;
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
  .cta p {
    color: var(--color-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
